	extbf{Experimental Setup}

\subsection{Design and Objectives}
We have constructed a comprehensive experimental setup to validate the proposed \emph{Graph-GaussianAssembler} methodology. This framework addresses key research questions encompassing robustness evaluation, state-of-the-art benchmarking, and the effectiveness of graph-based Gaussian reassembly. The experimental design ensures reproducibility through transparent configurations and a systematic approach to analysis and evaluation.

\subsection{Data Integration}
To assess the real-world applicability of the proposed method, we selected datasets representing diverse geometric and textural complexities. These include, but are not limited to, synthetic collections with well-defined Gaussian distributions and real-world datasets to test adaptability. Each dataset includes input prompts and corresponding reference structures to ensure meaningful comparison metrics.

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}
The following metrics were employed for quantitative and qualitative analysis:
 egin{itemize}
    \item 	extbf{Chamfer Distance} to evaluate point cloud geometric similarity.
    \item 	extbf{Gaussian Node Redundancy Reduction}, measuring optimizations in Gaussian clustering.
    \item 	extbf{Visual Quality Assessment} through rendered output clarity observed by domain experts.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Hardware and Software Setup}
All experiments were conducted on systems equipped with NVIDIA Tesla A100 GPUs and software comprising PyTorch for implementing deep-learning models, PyTorch Geometric for graph-processing techniques, and PyTorch3D for differentiable rendering, ensuring efficiency in computation.

